{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"170e9b1d-42f0-4bcb-9d93-37326aa9afec","content":"## What happened\n\nApple's native crypto libraries (`Security.framework` / `CryptoKit`) **do not support DSA**. .NET on macOS delegates to those native libraries for algorithm implementations. Microsoft has been progressively removing DSA support on macOS, and in .NET 11 `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on that platform. Linux (OpenSSL) and Windows (CNG) still have DSA support, which is why those targets continue to work.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify legacy signatures** (not create new ones), you have two practical options:\n\n### Option 1 – Use BouncyCastle (recommended)\nAdd the `BouncyCastle.Cryptography` NuGet package, which has a fully **managed** DSA implementation that runs everywhere:\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nbool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters publicKey)\n{\n    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA-1withDSA\"); // or SHA-256withDSA\n    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\n    verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\n    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\n### Option 2 – Runtime guard with platform check\nIf BouncyCastle is too heavy, you can conditionally call OpenSSL via P/Invoke on macOS while keeping the built-in `DSA` class on Windows/Linux:\n\n```csharp\nif (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n{\n    using var dsa = DSA.Create();\n    // ... built-in verification\n}\nelse\n{\n    // BouncyCastle or OpenSSL interop fallback\n}\n```\n\n### Going forward\nMigrate new signatures to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** — both are supported natively on all three platforms and are cryptographically stronger than DSA.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"923513aa-030a-4b9d-869f-21a5459df623","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms, and DSA specifically has been affected on macOS.\n\nLet me recall the details:\n\nIn .NET 7, Microsoft announced that several older cryptographic algorithms would throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because Apple's Security framework (and CommonCrypto/CryptoKit) dropped support for DSA. \n\nOn other platforms, DSA still works—Linux uses OpenSSL and Windows uses CNG/CAPI for these operations. But on macOS, since .NET relies on Apple's native crypto stack, DSA became unsupported. The user is upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, and given the current date is May 2026, .NET 10 would be the current LTS release.\n\nWait, let me reconsider the timeline here. .NET releases happen annually in November, so .NET 7 came out in November 2022, .NET 8 in November 2023, .NET 9 in November 2024, and .NET 10 would be November 2025. That means .NET 11 would be coming in November 2026. So the user is asking about a hypothetical future scenario.\n\nThe real issue is that DSA on macOS was broken starting in .NET 7, so if their code was working on .NET 10 on macOS, something doesn't add up—either they were using a workaround or there's something else going on with their setup. The deprecation has been gradual—obsolete warnings came first, then the `PlatformNotSupportedException` started being thrown. It's possible DSA worked through OpenSSL in some versions even after Apple's native implementation was removed, so the exact breaking point might vary. Given the user's scenario where it works on .NET 10 but breaks on .NET 11, I should focus on the core issue: Apple's security frameworks don't support DSA, so Microsoft removed the DSA implementation on macOS, causing `DSA.Create()` to throw the exception.\n\nFor workarounds, if they only need to verify existing DSA signatures, they could use a managed implementation like BouncyCastle, manually parse DSA parameters with `System.Formats.Asn1`, or use OpenSSL interop. The best path forward is migrating to a modern algorithm like ECDSA or Ed25519. I should give a straightforward answer since this is a knowledge question about a real, documented breaking change.","outputTokens":1815,"requestId":"3015:210854:16F8FD1:19BB8DD:6A067B52"},"id":"2a45b798-993d-4f3c-8cb7-004965dbfd39","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:48:41.889Z","parentId":"e667fb4c-61c2-4a2f-8e26-528060b561ae"}
